[The rapid, wide spread of ASF in Viet Nam is of great concern. Since 19 Feb 2019, and as of 20 Mar 2019, 207 outbreaks of ASF have been officially reported in 20 provinces/cities, as follows: Thai Binh (n=89), Hai Phong (n=33), Hung Yen (n=28), Hai Duong (n=17), Ha Noi (n=12), Ha Nam (n=5), Dien Bien (n=4), Quang Ninh (n=3), Thanh Hoa (n=2), Thai Nguyen (n=2), Bac Ninh (n=2), Ha Tay (n=2), Hoa Binh (n=1), Lang Son (n=1), Bac Kan (n=1), Nam Dinh (n=1), Nghe An (n=1), Ninh Binh (n=1) and Son La (n=1).

The data from China are the following. Since 1 Aug 2018, and as of 20 Mar 2019, ASF was officially detected in a total of 116 villages/sites in 27 Provinces/Autonomous regions/Municipalities out of 34: Liaoning (n=22), Anhui (n=9), Hunan (n=8), Sichuan (n=6), Heilongjiang (n=6, of which one in wild boar), Inner Mongolia (n=6), Yunnan (n=6), Shanxi (n=5), Beijing (n=4), Hubei (n=4), Jilin (n=4, of which one in a wild boar), Guizhou (n=4), Shaanxi (n=4), Fujian (n=3), Jiangxi (n=3), Guangdong (n=3), Zhejiang (n=3), Jiangsu (n=3), Guangxi (n=2), Henan (n=2), Tianjin (n=2), Chongqing (n=2), Qinghai (n=1), Ningxia (n=1), Gansu (n=1), Shandong (n=1) and Hebei (n=1).

The gap between the ASF statistics in Viet Nam (207 outbreaks in one month), and China (116 outbreaks in more than 7 months) is striking. When one refers to the picture illuminated in item 1 above, suspected under-reporting of ASF in China seems plausible. - Mod.AS

